  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Hidden Sugar: Where Calories Hide Without You Knowing</h2>
    <p>Most people underestimate sugar in foods marketed as "healthy." Here are the most common hidden sources:</p>
    <div class="card" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden;margin:16px 0;">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Food</th><th>Portion</th><th>Sugar</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Flavoured yoghurt</td><td>150g pot</td><td>15–22g</td><td>Often as much as a chocolate bar</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Shop-bought fruit smoothie</td><td>250ml</td><td>25–35g</td><td>Fibre removed; rapid blood sugar spike</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Granola / muesli</td><td>60g serving</td><td>12–18g</td><td>Often higher sugar than breakfast cereal</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Jar pasta sauce</td><td>150g</td><td>10–15g</td><td>Added sugar for flavour balance</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sports drinks</td><td>500ml bottle</td><td>30–38g</td><td>Only useful for &gt;90 min intense exercise</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Low-fat salad dressing</td><td>2 tbsp</td><td>6–10g</td><td>Fat replaced with sugar for palatability</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The "low-fat" category is particularly worth watching: when fat is removed, manufacturers often add sugar to maintain taste. A low-fat yoghurt may have 50% more sugar than its full-fat equivalent.</p>

    <div style="margin-top:20px;">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does sugar directly cause weight gain?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">Not directly — weight gain is caused by a sustained calorie surplus, regardless of where those calories come from. However, sugar makes overeating easy: it is highly palatable, digests quickly (providing little satiety), and is found in ultra-processed foods engineered to override normal fullness signals. Studies comparing high-sugar vs low-sugar diets at equal calorie intake find similar weight outcomes. The problem is sugar's contribution to excess calorie intake, not a special fat-producing effect.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much sugar per day is too much?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">The WHO recommends limiting free sugars (added sugars plus juice and honey — not sugars in whole fruit or milk) to less than 10% of total energy intake, with a further reduction to below 5% for additional benefits. For a 2,000 kcal/day diet, 10% = 50g and 5% = 25g. The average UK adult consumes ~59g/day; the average US adult ~77g/day. Sugars in whole fruit, vegetables, and plain dairy do not count toward these limits.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is fruit sugar bad for weight loss?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">No — whole fruit is not a meaningful contributor to weight gain for most people. Whole fruit contains fibre, water, and micronutrients that slow sugar absorption and promote satiety. Research consistently links high whole fruit intake to healthy weight and lower metabolic disease risk. Fruit juice is different: fibre is removed, so sugar absorbs rapidly with minimal satiety. Prioritise whole fruit over juice, and be mindful of large portions of high-sugar fruits (mangoes, grapes, bananas) if tracking calories closely.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

